e)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bowie","meanings":["Scottish: from Gaelic <i>buidhe</i> ‘yellow’, i.e. ‘yellow-haired’, pronounced as two syllables. The equivalent term in Ireland is <i>buí</i>, often Anglicized as <i>boy</i>. The surname may also be a shortened form of   Gilboy  .","Irish: Anglicized form of <b>Ó Buadhaigh</b> (see   Bogue  )."]},{"name":"Boyde","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): variant of   Boyd  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Boyd was born in 1360, in Renfrewshire, Scotland, his father, Thomas Boyd, was 38 and his mother, Margaret Douglas, was 40. He married Alice Gifford in 1384, in Yester Castle, Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1410, in Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1360–1410":"1360–1410","1354–Male":"1354–Surnud","1362–Male":"1362–Surnud","1364–Female":"1364–Surnud","1375–1405":"1375–1405","1375–1432":"1375–1432","1323–1367":"1323–1367","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","October 1367":"oktoober 1367","1384":"1384","1362":"1362","1360":"1360","Abt 1410":"umbes 1410","1367":"1367","1323":"1323","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1354":"1354","1375":"1375","1320":"1320","1364":"1364","1405":"1405","Kilmarnock, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Kilmarnock, , Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Yester Castle, Yester, Haddingtonsh